  "event_preview": "Okayama International Circuit is a 3.703 km (2.301 mi) road course in Mimasaka, Okayama Prefecture, Japan - a compact, technically demanding layout featuring 11 corners, a track width of 12-15 metres and 29 metres of elevation change. Originally opened in 1990 as a private motor racing facility and best known for hosting the 1994 and 1995 Formula One Pacific Grand Prix, it has served as the Super GT season opener since 2021. The Okayama GT 300km Race is Round 1 of the 2026 AUTOBACS SUPER GT Series, contested over 82 laps (303.6 km) with a full 43-car grid - 14 in GT500 and 29 in GT300. Both classes race simultaneously, and the gap between GT500 and GT300 lap times - roughly seven seconds - means mixed-class traffic is a constant strategic variable throughout the race. This is also one of only two rounds without Balance of Performance active, making it a clean benchmark for each car's natural performance level. The GT500 qualifying lap record belongs to Nirei Fukuzumi, who turned a 1:16.441 in the No. 14 ENEOS X PRIME GR Supra during Q2 at the 2025 season opener. The GT300 qualifying lap record belongs to Hideki Yamauchi, who set a 1:24.286 in the No. 61 Subaru BRZ R&D Sport during Q2 at the 2022 opening round - a mark that has now stood for four seasons.",
